<div id="review_3050582637" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3050582637" />
    <a title="Michelle" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5858203-michelle"><img alt="Michelle" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1520844755p2/5858203.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3050582637?book_show_action=true">Nov 16, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michelle" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michelle" href="/user/show/5858203-michelle">Michelle</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook " href="/book/show/8310690-carmilla">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3050582637" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6324890023144755442">This book was published in 1872 and is said to be the book that later inspired Dracula, it was brought to my attention by a fellow book dragon Salema and I couldn&apos;t wait to read it.<br/><br/>It&apos;s a short novella at 108 pages and is available as a free download so if you&apos;re into your vampires get downloading! <br/><br/>I read this in one sitting, it&apos;s so readable for a book written so long ago and I must say I enjoyed it. I&apos;m coming to realise that I do enjoy a book where the narration is directed at the reader, it </span>
  <span id="freeText6324890023144755442" style="display:none">This book was published in 1872 and is said to be the book that later inspired Dracula, it was brought to my attention by a fellow book dragon Salema and I couldn't wait to read it.<br /><br />It's a short novella at 108 pages and is available as a free download so if you're into your vampires get downloading! <br /><br />I read this in one sitting, it's so readable for a book written so long ago and I must say I enjoyed it. I'm coming to realise that I do enjoy a book where the narration is directed at the reader, it makes me feel a part of the cast and really improves the atmosphere the author is creating. <br /><br />This isnt the best vampire book out there but as one of the earliest vampire novellas and one that features female / female attractions I do feel this is worth a read, especially as it's so short and of course free!<br /><br />As with many classics I rate this three stars, its readable, its aged well but it didnt blow me away.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6324890023144755442" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


