  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1617930226" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1617930226" />
    <a title="Tom Lewis" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41086818-tom-lewis"><img alt="Tom Lewis" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1428092317p2/41086818.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1617930226?book_show_action=true">Apr 22, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tom Lewis" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tom Lewis" href="/user/show/41086818-tom-lewis">Tom Lewis</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1617930226" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5829501586201132774">“But to die as lovers may - to die together, so that they may live together.”<br/><br/>Okay, how many vampire books have you read that contain that kind of elegant prose. Carmilla is a novella that was written in 1872, so it pre-dates Dracula by about 25 years. And a lot of its influence is later seen in Dracula.<br/><br/>Being as old as it is, there’s no twists that will catch a modern reader by surprise, as pretty much every variation on the vampire genre has been played out. But what you will find is something s</span>
  <span id="freeText5829501586201132774" style="display:none">“But to die as lovers may - to die together, so that they may live together.”<br /><br />Okay, how many vampire books have you read that contain that kind of elegant prose. Carmilla is a novella that was written in 1872, so it pre-dates Dracula by about 25 years. And a lot of its influence is later seen in Dracula.<br /><br />Being as old as it is, there’s no twists that will catch a modern reader by surprise, as pretty much every variation on the vampire genre has been played out. But what you will find is something sorely lacking in modern vampire literature – a rich gothic tapestry of remote castles, and dark forests; of horse-drawn carriages, misty mountains, and superstitious peasantry; and a quiet melancholy that permeates what is at times a touching tale (with sapphic undercurrents) of a young vampire torn by the need to kill the people she loves.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5829501586201132774" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

